From: jaewun <jaewun@users.noreply.github.com>
Subject: [PATCH] scsi: ufs: service out-of-band relink completions during PM and self-heal clk-gating hibern8-exit

On this non-MCQ controller the UFS interrupt is request_threaded_irq(IRQF_ONESHOT
| IRQF_SHARED) on a GIC-v3 SPI. When the primary handler returns IRQ_WAKE_THREAD,
genirq keeps the line masked until the threaded handler's irq_finalize_oneshot()
runs. If that threaded handler is left pending-but-unrunnable across a PM
transition, the line stays masked, ufshcd_intr() is never re-entered, and the cold
relink's UIC/UTP completions latch in REG_INTERRUPT_STATUS forever -- the relink
hangs and, with no hardware watchdog, the device wedges until a manual power-cycle.

This bites hardest on the error-handler reset path. ufshcd_err_handler() diverts
PM-context errors to link_recovery, so the reset_and_restore() it runs has
pm_op_in_progress already cleared. The error IRQ that triggered the handler left
the line IRQF_ONESHOT-masked and the relink's non-synchronising disable_irq() keeps
genirq from unmasking it, so ufshcd_intr() is never re-invoked and nothing services
the relink's completions.

Service them without depending on the UFS IRQ firing:

  - ufshcd_pm_drain_completions() services UTP/UIC/TMF completions and read-clears
    the UIC error-code registers (storm prevention). It runs from ufshcd_intr()'s
    PM fast path (hardirq) and from an arch-timer poller (pm_poll_timer).

  - ufshcd_relinking() (pm_op_in_progress || relink_poll_active) scopes the drain
    to both the PM-resume relink and the EH reset_and_restore window; the EH arms
    relink_poll_active + the poll timer around the reset and disarms after. It also
    gates the non-synchronising disable_irq so the PM/EH path cannot deadlock on
    the threaded handler it pre-empted.

  - A stalled cold-relink DME_LINK_STARTUP (UIC error, no completion) is
    force-completed with UIC_CMD_RESULT_FAILURE so link startup can retry rather
    than wait forever.

  - On the reset_and_restore() path, ufshcd_complete_requests(force_compl=true)
    only completed door-bell-cleared tags on this non-MCQ controller, so a request
    stranded on a failed UIC/link op was never completed and its waiter -- a
    SYNCHRONIZE CACHE issued from sd_suspend() during system suspend -- hung until
    the DPM watchdog panicked. ufshcd_force_compl_one() now mirrors the MCQ force
    path: every outstanding command is requeued with DID_REQUEUE so it retries on
    the recovered link instead of stranding. The stale post-reset in-memory OCS is
    not trusted.

The SW clk-gating ungate hibern8 EXIT (ufshcd_ungate_work) runs during the suspend
freezer phase with pm_op_in_progress==0. On the SM8550/SKhynix M-PHY it can
-ETIMEDOUT when the link gated during a sub-ms micro-idle and I/O then needs it
back. The default ufshcd_uic_pwr_ctrl path would mark the link broken and queue a
fatal EH, which during the freeze strands in-flight ext4/jbd2 fsync I/O in D-state,
fails the freezer, and hard-wedges the box. Mirror the runtime-resume self-heal:
recover the link in-line via ufshcd_link_recovery() instead of going fatal,
bracketed by the same relink poller so the out-of-band drain covers the relink's
link-startup, and add !clk_gating.is_suspended to the ufshcd_uic_pwr_ctrl fatal
guard so the clk-gating ungate window no longer trips set_link_broken +
schedule_eh_work. SW clk-gating hibern8 (idle power) is preserved.

At dev-init-NOP time REG_INTERRUPT_ENABLE is already full, so the IS-gated drain
reaps the NOP completion directly; no doorbell-level reap is needed.

Validated by RTC deep-suspend soaks (>=120s cold-rail dwell), bare and in a live
gamescope/Steam session: the relink that previously wedged within 1-2 cycles now
survives sustained deep-dwell cycling.

Signed-off-by: jaewun <jaewun@users.noreply.github.com>
---
--- a/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
+++ b/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
@@ -348,6 +348,24 @@
 static void ufshcd_hba_vreg_set_lpm(struct ufs_hba *hba);
 static void ufshcd_hba_vreg_set_hpm(struct ufs_hba *hba);
 
+/*
+ * True while the controller is being relinked and the threaded IRQ handler
+ * cannot be relied upon -- either a PM suspend/resume (pm_op_in_progress) or the
+ * specific error-handler reset bracket (relink_poll_active, set around
+ * ufshcd_reset_and_restore() in ufshcd_err_handler() when pm_op_in_progress is
+ * already clear). In both, ufshcd_disable_irq() must not synchronize on the
+ * (possibly stuck/masked) thread and completions must be drained out-of-band
+ * rather than waited on via the IRQ. The error-handler case is how a marginal
+ * cold link wedges under post-resume I/O load (e.g. Steam). A dedicated flag is
+ * used rather than UFSHCD_STATE_RESET so generic resets/probe are unaffected.
+ * Lock-free cross-context reads -> READ_ONCE.
+ */
+static inline bool ufshcd_relinking(struct ufs_hba *hba)
+{
+	return READ_ONCE(hba->pm_op_in_progress) ||
+	       READ_ONCE(hba->relink_poll_active);
+}
+
 void ufshcd_enable_irq(struct ufs_hba *hba)
 {
 	if (!hba->is_irq_enabled) {
@@ -360,7 +378,24 @@
 void ufshcd_disable_irq(struct ufs_hba *hba)
 {
 	if (hba->is_irq_enabled) {
-		disable_irq(hba->irq);
+		/*
+		 * hba->irq is a threaded, IRQF_ONESHOT interrupt. The synchronous
+		 * disable_irq() runs synchronize_irq(), which waits for the threaded
+		 * handler (ufshcd_threaded_intr) to finish. During a PM operation the
+		 * threaded handler is not relied upon -- resume-time completions are
+		 * serviced inline in hardirq -- and it may be unscheduled (the
+		 * deep-resume PM phase) or stuck on the resuming controller. Waiting
+		 * for it then HARD-WEDGES the resume relink: this is reached from the
+		 * ufshcd_hba_enable() retry in ufshcd_link_startup() via both
+		 * ufshcd_hba_stop() and the qcom ufs_qcom_host_reset() PRE_CHANGE
+		 * hook. Mask without synchronizing while relinking (PM resume OR an
+		 * error-handler reset); the controller reset and out-of-band completion
+		 * servicing handle any in-flight state.
+		 */
+		if (ufshcd_relinking(hba))
+			disable_irq_nosync(hba->irq);
+		else
+			disable_irq(hba->irq);
 		hba->is_irq_enabled = false;
 	}
 }
@@ -1921,11 +1956,40 @@
 		hba->clk_gating.is_suspended = true;
 		if (ufshcd_is_link_hibern8(hba)) {
 			ret = ufshcd_uic_hibern8_exit(hba);
-			if (ret)
-				dev_err(hba->dev, "%s: hibern8 exit failed %d\n",
+			if (ret) {
+				/*
+				 * This SW clk-gating hibern8 exit runs outside any
+				 * PM op (pm_op_in_progress == 0) with IRQs enabled.
+				 * On this M-PHY it can -ETIMEDOUT; the default path
+				 * (ufshcd_uic_pwr_ctrl) would then mark the link
+				 * broken and schedule a fatal EH, which during the
+				 * suspend freeze strands in-flight fsync I/O and
+				 * wedges the box. Instead self-heal in-line via a
+				 * cold relink, mirroring the runtime-resume path.
+				 * Bracket it with the relink poller (inert on MCQ)
+				 * so the out-of-band completion drain covers the
+				 * relink's link-startup. The fatal EH for this exit
+				 * is suppressed by the !clk_gating.is_suspended term
+				 * in ufshcd_uic_pwr_ctrl.
+				 */
+				dev_err(hba->dev, "%s: hibern8 exit failed %d, recovering link\n",
 					__func__, ret);
-			else
+				if (!hba->mcq_enabled) {
+					WRITE_ONCE(hba->relink_poll_active, true);
+					mod_timer(&hba->pm_poll_timer,
+						  jiffies + msecs_to_jiffies(2));
+				}
+				ret = ufshcd_link_recovery(hba);
+				if (!hba->mcq_enabled) {
+					WRITE_ONCE(hba->relink_poll_active, false);
+					timer_delete_sync(&hba->pm_poll_timer);
+				}
+				if (ret)
+					dev_err(hba->dev, "%s: link recovery after hibern8 exit failed %d\n",
+						__func__, ret);
+			} else {
 				ufshcd_set_link_active(hba);
+			}
 		}
 		hba->clk_gating.is_suspended = false;
 	}
@@ -4382,7 +4446,15 @@
 	spin_lock_irqsave(hba->host->host_lock, flags);
 	hba->active_uic_cmd = NULL;
 	hba->uic_async_done = NULL;
-	if (ret && !hba->pm_op_in_progress) {
+	/*
+	 * Suppress the fatal link-broken+EH path for the SW clk-gating ungate
+	 * hibern8 exit (clk_gating.is_suspended is set only in that window and the
+	 * PM-suspend path, which already has pm_op_in_progress). That exit runs
+	 * outside any PM op, so without this term a transient hibern8-exit -110
+	 * would wedge the box during the suspend freeze; ufshcd_ungate_work
+	 * instead self-heals via ufshcd_link_recovery.
+	 */
+	if (ret && !hba->pm_op_in_progress && !hba->clk_gating.is_suspended) {
 		ufshcd_set_link_broken(hba);
 		ufshcd_schedule_eh_work(hba);
 	}
@@ -6383,11 +6455,55 @@
 	ufs_debugfs_exception_event(hba, status);
 }
 
-/* Complete requests that have door-bell cleared */
+/*
+ * Non-MCQ counterpart of ufshcd_mcq_force_compl_one(): invoked via
+ * ufshcd_complete_requests(force_compl=true) from ufshcd_host_reset_and_restore()
+ * (and the error handler) AFTER ufshcd_hba_stop() has reset the controller. The
+ * normal single-doorbell path (ufshcd_transfer_req_compl/ufshcd_poll) only
+ * completes tags whose doorbell bit reads back clear, so a request left
+ * outstanding by a failed UIC/link op (e.g. the SW clk-gating hibern8-exit
+ * recovered in ufshcd_ungate_work) is never completed and its waiter hangs --
+ * a SYNCHRONIZE CACHE in sd_suspend() then wedges the box until the DPM watchdog
+ * panics. The in-memory OCS is stale after the reset, so requeue SCSI commands
+ * (retry on the recovered link) rather than reporting a possibly-bogus result;
+ * reserved device-management tags are completed by their own paths and skipped
+ * (mirrors ufshcd_mcq_force_compl_one()).
+ */
+static bool ufshcd_force_compl_one(struct request *rq, void *priv)
+{
+	struct scsi_cmnd *cmd = blk_mq_rq_to_pdu(rq);
+	struct scsi_device *sdev = rq->q->queuedata;
+	struct ufs_hba *hba = shost_priv(sdev->host);
+	unsigned long flags;
+
+	if (blk_mq_is_reserved_rq(rq))
+		return true;
+
+	spin_lock_irqsave(&hba->outstanding_lock, flags);
+	__clear_bit(rq->tag, &hba->outstanding_reqs);
+	spin_unlock_irqrestore(&hba->outstanding_lock, flags);
+
+	if (!test_bit(SCMD_STATE_COMPLETE, &cmd->state)) {
+		set_host_byte(cmd, DID_REQUEUE);
+		ufshcd_release_scsi_cmd(hba, cmd);
+		scsi_done(cmd);
+	}
+
+	return true;
+}
+
+/* Complete requests that have door-bell cleared (or, on force, all outstanding) */
 static void ufshcd_complete_requests(struct ufs_hba *hba, bool force_compl)
 {
 	if (hba->mcq_enabled)
 		ufshcd_mcq_compl_pending_transfer(hba, force_compl);
+	else if (force_compl)
+		/*
+		 * The controller has been reset; complete every outstanding
+		 * request (the doorbell no longer reflects them) so none strand.
+		 */
+		blk_mq_tagset_busy_iter(&hba->host->tag_set,
+					ufshcd_force_compl_one, NULL);
 	else
 		ufshcd_transfer_req_compl(hba);
 
@@ -6863,6 +6979,17 @@
 
 		hba->force_reset = false;
 		spin_unlock_irqrestore(hba->host->host_lock, flags);
+		/*
+		 * Arm the out-of-band completion poller across the error-handler
+		 * relink. ufshcd_state == UFSHCD_STATE_RESET here and pm_op_in_progress
+		 * is clear, so ufshcd_relinking() gates the drain (and the nosync
+		 * disable_irq) on. This is the path a marginal cold link wedges through
+		 * under post-resume I/O load (e.g. Steam), with pm_op already cleared.
+		 */
+		if (!hba->mcq_enabled) {
+			WRITE_ONCE(hba->relink_poll_active, true);
+			mod_timer(&hba->pm_poll_timer, jiffies + msecs_to_jiffies(2));
+		}
 		err = ufshcd_reset_and_restore(hba);
 		if (err)
 			dev_err(hba->dev, "%s: reset and restore failed with err %d\n",
@@ -6889,6 +7016,14 @@
 	}
 	ufshcd_clear_eh_in_progress(hba);
 	spin_unlock_irqrestore(hba->host->host_lock, flags);
+	/*
+	 * Stop the relink poller before unprepare can release the clocks. Clear the
+	 * flag first so the callback sees ufshcd_relinking() false and will not
+	 * re-arm, then synchronously delete. Done after the host_lock is dropped
+	 * (the drain takes host_lock).
+	 */
+	WRITE_ONCE(hba->relink_poll_active, false);
+	timer_delete_sync(&hba->pm_poll_timer);
 	ufshcd_err_handling_unprepare(hba);
 	up(&hba->host_sem);
 
@@ -7207,6 +7342,115 @@
 	return retval;
 }
 
+/*
+ * ufshcd_pm_drain_completions - service UTP/UIC/TMF completions without the IRQ
+ * @hba: per adapter instance
+ *
+ * The UFS interrupt is a threaded IRQF_ONESHOT line. If its threaded handler is
+ * left pending-but-unrunnable across a PM transition the genirq core keeps the
+ * line masked, so ufshcd_intr() is never re-invoked and the cold-resume relink's
+ * completions latch in REG_INTERRUPT_STATUS forever (UIC link-startup and the
+ * first dev-cmd NOP both wait_for_completion()). Drain and service them directly.
+ * Called inline from ufshcd_intr()'s PM fast path (hardirq) AND from the PM poll
+ * timer (softirq), so it must not depend on the UFS IRQ firing. pm_drain_active
+ * serialises the two callers so they cannot both W1C REG_INTERRUPT_STATUS.
+ */
+static void ufshcd_pm_drain_completions(struct ufs_hba *hba)
+{
+	int retries = hba->nutrs;
+
+	if (test_and_set_bit(0, &hba->pm_drain_active))
+		return;
+
+	while (retries-- > 0) {
+		unsigned long flags;
+		u32 status, compl_bits;
+
+		status = ufshcd_readl(hba, REG_INTERRUPT_STATUS) &
+			 ufshcd_readl(hba, REG_INTERRUPT_ENABLE);
+		if (!status)
+			break;
+
+		/* W1C exactly the snapshot we read. */
+		ufshcd_writel(hba, status, REG_INTERRUPT_STATUS);
+
+		if (status & UFSHCD_ERROR_MASK) {
+			/*
+			 * read-to-clear all UIC error-code registers so a
+			 * transient resume-time error cannot storm.
+			 */
+			ufshcd_readl(hba, REG_UIC_ERROR_CODE_PHY_ADAPTER_LAYER);
+			ufshcd_readl(hba, REG_UIC_ERROR_CODE_DATA_LINK_LAYER);
+			ufshcd_readl(hba, REG_UIC_ERROR_CODE_NETWORK_LAYER);
+			ufshcd_readl(hba, REG_UIC_ERROR_CODE_TRANSPORT_LAYER);
+			ufshcd_readl(hba, REG_UIC_ERROR_CODE_DME);
+
+			/*
+			 * If the relink's in-flight UIC command (e.g.
+			 * DME_LINKSTARTUP) errored with no accompanying UIC
+			 * completion, force-complete it with UIC_CMD_RESULT_FAILURE
+			 * so ufshcd_wait_for_uic_cmd() returns promptly and the
+			 * relink retries/rescues. Restricted to DME_LINK_STARTUP
+			 * with no uic_async_done in flight so power-mode UIC
+			 * commands are untouched. irqsave: this also runs in
+			 * softirq (the PM poll timer).
+			 */
+			spin_lock_irqsave(hba->host->host_lock, flags);
+			if (!(status & UFSHCD_UIC_MASK) && !hba->uic_async_done &&
+			    hba->active_uic_cmd &&
+			    hba->active_uic_cmd->cmd_active &&
+			    hba->active_uic_cmd->command ==
+				    UIC_CMD_DME_LINK_STARTUP) {
+				struct uic_command *cmd = hba->active_uic_cmd;
+
+				cmd->argument2 = (cmd->argument2 &
+						  ~MASK_UIC_COMMAND_RESULT) |
+						 UIC_CMD_RESULT_FAILURE;
+				cmd->cmd_active = false;
+				complete(&cmd->done);
+			}
+			spin_unlock_irqrestore(hba->host->host_lock, flags);
+		}
+
+		compl_bits = status & (UTP_TRANSFER_REQ_COMPL | UFSHCD_UIC_MASK);
+		if (compl_bits & UFSHCD_UIC_MASK)
+			ufshcd_uic_cmd_compl(hba, compl_bits);
+		if (status & UTP_TASK_REQ_COMPL)
+			ufshcd_tmc_handler(hba);
+		if (compl_bits & UTP_TRANSFER_REQ_COMPL)
+			ufshcd_transfer_req_compl(hba);
+	}
+
+	clear_bit(0, &hba->pm_drain_active);
+}
+
+/*
+ * ufshcd_pm_poll_timer_fn - out-of-band UFS completion drain during PM resume.
+ *
+ * Armed across the deep-resume relink window. Fires off the arch timer, so it
+ * services UFS completions even when the (oneshot-masked) UFS IRQ line never
+ * re-invokes ufshcd_intr(). Self-rearms while pm_op_in_progress; the resume
+ * path clears the flag and timer_delete_sync()s it on the way out.
+ */
+static void ufshcd_pm_poll_timer_fn(struct timer_list *t)
+{
+	struct ufs_hba *hba = timer_container_of(hba, t, pm_poll_timer);
+
+	if (hba->mcq_enabled || !ufshcd_relinking(hba))
+		return;
+
+	ufshcd_pm_drain_completions(hba);
+
+	/*
+	 * Re-check before re-arming so a concurrent disarm (which clears the
+	 * relink state before timer_delete_sync()) cannot lose the race and leave
+	 * the timer armed. A stray re-arm would be harmless anyway -- the next tick
+	 * sees the state clear and returns without MMIO -- but avoid it.
+	 */
+	if (ufshcd_relinking(hba))
+		mod_timer(&hba->pm_poll_timer, jiffies + msecs_to_jiffies(2));
+}
+
 /**
  * ufshcd_intr - Main interrupt service routine
  * @irq: irq number
@@ -7222,6 +7466,23 @@
 	struct ufs_hba *hba = __hba;
 	u32 intr_status, enabled_intr_status;
 
+	/*
+	 * On this non-MCQ controller interrupt handling is normally deferred to
+	 * the threaded handler, which is not scheduled during the deep-resume PM
+	 * phase. That leaves completed UTP/UIC commands latched in IS but never
+	 * serviced (the relink's first command waits forever), and a latched
+	 * UIC_ERROR re-fires the level IRQ forever (storm). While the controller
+	 * is resuming, service UTP/UIC/TMF completions inline in hardirq, and
+	 * W1C-ack + read-clear the UIC error-code registers so a transient
+	 * resume-time error cannot storm. Do not run ufshcd_check_errors() from
+	 * hardirq (it would schedule the error handler / link recovery, which is
+	 * reentrant during PM).
+	 */
+	if (!hba->mcq_enabled && ufshcd_relinking(hba)) {
+		ufshcd_pm_drain_completions(hba);
+		return IRQ_HANDLED;
+	}
+
 	/* Move interrupt handling to thread when MCQ & ESI are not enabled */
 	if (!hba->mcq_enabled || !hba->mcq_esi_enabled)
 		return IRQ_WAKE_THREAD;
@@ -9729,6 +9990,7 @@
 
 static void ufshcd_hba_exit(struct ufs_hba *hba)
 {
+	timer_delete_sync(&hba->pm_poll_timer);
 	if (hba->is_powered) {
 		ufshcd_pm_qos_exit(hba);
 		ufshcd_exit_clk_scaling(hba);
@@ -10182,6 +10444,17 @@
 	if (ret)
 		goto out;
 
+	/*
+	 * Vendor resume is done so the controller clocks/registers are usable.
+	 * Arm the out-of-band completion poller for the relink: the UFS IRQ may
+	 * be oneshot-masked (threaded handler pending-but-unrunnable across the PM
+	 * transition), in which case ufshcd_intr() never fires and the relink's
+	 * UIC/UTP completions are never serviced. The timer drains them off the
+	 * arch timer instead. Disarmed at out: before pm_op_in_progress is cleared.
+	 */
+	if (!hba->mcq_enabled)
+		mod_timer(&hba->pm_poll_timer, jiffies + msecs_to_jiffies(2));
+
 	/* For DeepSleep, the only supported option is to have the link off */
 	WARN_ON(ufshcd_is_ufs_dev_deepsleep(hba) && !ufshcd_is_link_off(hba));
 
@@ -10259,9 +10532,18 @@
 out:
 	if (ret)
 		ufshcd_update_evt_hist(hba, UFS_EVT_WL_RES_ERR, (u32)ret);
+	/*
+	 * Stop the relink completion poller BEFORE ufshcd_release() (which can
+	 * queue clock gating once is_suspended is cleared) so the timer can never
+	 * read UFS MMIO after the clocks are gated. Clear pm_op_in_progress first so
+	 * a concurrently-firing timer sees the flag false and does not re-arm, then
+	 * synchronously delete it. From here normal IRQ delivery resumes: the
+	 * now-runnable threaded handler drains any remaining IS and unmasks the line.
+	 */
+	hba->pm_op_in_progress = false;
+	timer_delete_sync(&hba->pm_poll_timer);
 	hba->clk_gating.is_suspended = false;
 	ufshcd_release(hba);
-	hba->pm_op_in_progress = false;
 	return ret;
 }
 
@@ -10884,6 +11166,13 @@
 	 */
 	hba->vcc_off_delay_us = 2000;
 
+	/*
+	 * Set up the relink completion poll timer before the first goto out_disable
+	 * (which reaches ufshcd_hba_exit() -> timer_delete_sync()), so teardown
+	 * never operates on an uninitialised timer.
+	 */
+	timer_setup(&hba->pm_poll_timer, ufshcd_pm_poll_timer_fn, 0);
+
 	err = ufshcd_hba_init(hba);
 	if (err)
 		goto out_error;
--- a/include/ufs/ufshcd.h
+++ b/include/ufs/ufshcd.h
@@ -976,6 +976,22 @@
 	enum ufs_pm_level pm_lvl_min;
 	int pm_op_in_progress;
 
+	/*
+	 * Thor: out-of-band completion drain for the deep-resume relink. The UFS
+	 * IRQ is IRQF_ONESHOT; if its threaded handler is left pending-but-
+	 * unrunnable across the PM transition, genirq keeps the line masked and
+	 * ufshcd_intr() is never re-invoked, so the relink's UIC/UTP completions
+	 * latch in IS forever. pm_poll_timer fires off the arch timer (independent
+	 * of the masked UFS line) to drain completions while pm_op_in_progress.
+	 * pm_drain_active serialises the timer drain against the hardirq drain.
+	 * relink_poll_active extends the same protection to the error-handler reset
+	 * (which runs reset_and_restore with pm_op_in_progress clear) -- set only
+	 * across that explicit bracket, not for generic resets.
+	 */
+	struct timer_list pm_poll_timer;
+	unsigned long pm_drain_active;
+	bool relink_poll_active;
+
 	/* Auto-Hibernate Idle Timer register value */
 	u32 ahit;
 
